The paper deals with distributed information processing over networks, which is a topic that falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The use of geographic information and random geometric graphs suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of randomized message-passing algorithms, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). The focus on consensus and optimization suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). Finally, the use of Markov chain mixing time inequalities suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
